e [[European Broadcasting Union]] (EBU).<ref name=Eligibility>{{cite web|title=Which countries? FAQs |url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/about/which-countries-can-take-part#Which_countries? |publisher=Eurovision Song Contest |accessdate=22 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522144052/http://www.eurovision.tv/page/about/which-countries-can-take-part |archivedate=22 May 2014 }}</ref> The EBU issued an invitation of participation for the 2015 Contest to all 56 active members.<ref name=Eligibility/> Thirty-nine countries confirmed their participation,<ref name=\"Full list\"/> whilst the following list of countries declined stating their reasons as shown below.\n\n=== Active EBU members ===\n* {{Esc|Andorra}} \u2013 On 17 June 2014, Andorran broadcaster [[R\u00e0dio i Televisi\u00f3 d'Andorra]] (RTVA) confirmed that Andorra would not return to the contest in 2015.<ref name=\"Andorra\">{{cite web|first=Sanjay|last=Jiandani|title=Andorra: RTVA will not return to Eurovision in 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/84971/andorra-rtva-will-return-eurovision-2015/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=17 June 2014|date=17 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} \u2013 The Bosnian broadcaster, [[Radio and Television of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (BHRT), had submitted a provisional application to participate in the 2015 Contest,<ref name=\"Bosnia Return\">{{cite web|last1=Jiandani|first1=Sanjay|title=Bosnia & Herzegovina: BHRT confirms participation in Eurovision 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/86737/xx-xx-confirms-participation-eurovision-2015-5/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=9 September 2014|date=9 September 2014}}</ref> whilst they determined how to fund the participation fees.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jiandani|first1=Sanjay|title=Bosnia & Herzegovina: BHRT does not withdraw application for Eurovision 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/88086/bosnia-herzegovina-bhrt-confirms-participation-eurovision-2015/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=10 October 2014|date=10 October 2014}}</ref> This application was subject to change and participation could subsequently be withdrawn.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jiandani|first1=Sergio|title=Bosnia & Herzegovina: Participation in Vienna uncertain; deadline extended|url=http://esctoday.com/89323/bosnia-herzegovina-bhrt-confirms-participation-eurovision-2015-2/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=1 November 2014|date=31 October 2014}}</ref> On 17 November 2014, the broadcaster announced that they had withdrawn their application to participate at the forthcoming contest because of financial reasons.<ref>{{cite web|first=Sanjay|last=Jiandani|title=Bosnia & Herzegovina: BHRT will not return to Eurovision in 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/90077/bosnia-herzegovina-bhrt-will-return-eurovision-2015/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=17 November 2014|date=17 November 2014}}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Bulgaria}} \u2013 Despite sending a preliminary application to participate,<ref>{{cite web|first=Sanjay|last=Jiandani|title=Bulgaria: BNT confirms preliminary participation in Eurovision 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/86851/bulgaria-bnt-confirms-participation-eurovision-2015/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=20 September 2014|date=20 September 2014}}</ref> on 10 October 2014 the Bulgarian broadcaster [[Bulgarian National Television]] (BNT) announced that it would not return to the contest because of financial reasons.<ref>{{cite web|first=Sanjay|last=Jiandani|title=Bulgaria: BNT will not participate in Eurovision 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/87934/bulgaria-bnt-will-participate-vienna/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=10 October 2014|date=10 October 2014}}</ref> On 31 October 2014, BNT confirmed that they had not yet taken a final decision on participation at the 2015 contest, and that the EBU had given them extra time to resolve outstanding budget issues.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jiandani|first1=Sanjay|title=Bulgaria: No final decision on Eurovision 2015 yet|url=http://esctoday.com/89319/bulgaria-no-final-decision-eurovision-2015-ye/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=31 October 2014|date=31 October 2014}}</ref> However, on 18 December 2014, BNT confirmed via their official Eurovision Twitter account that they would not take part in the 2015 Contest.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jiandani|first1=Sanjay|title=Bulgaria: BNT will not participate in Eurovision 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/89999/bulgaria-bnt-will-not-participate-in-eurovision-2015/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=19 December 2014|date=19 December 2014}}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Croatia}} \u2013 On 26 September 2014, Croatian national broadcaster [[Croatian Radiotelevision]] (HRT) confirmed that Croatia would not participate in the 2015 contest.<ref>{{cite web|first=Sanjay|last=Jiandani|title=Croatia: HRT will not participate Eurovision 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/86890/croatia-hrt-eurovision-2015/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=26 September 2014|date=26 September 2014}}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Lebanon}} \u2013 [[T\u00e9l\u00e9 Liban]] (TL) confirmed on 15 September 2014 that Lebanon would not be making their debut in Vienna.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jiandani|first1=Sanjay|title=T\u00e9l\u00e9 Liben will not participate in Eurovision 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/86618/lebanon-tele-liban/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=15 September 2014|date=15 September 2014}}</ref> Lebanon were initially going to make their debut at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2005#Other countries|2005 contest]], but they pulled out prior to the contest due to financial reasons.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Philips|first1=Roel|title=Lebanon withdraws for financial reasons|url=http://esctoday.com/3485/lebanon_withdraws_for_financial_reasons/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=15 September 2014|date=15 December 2004}}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Luxembourg}} \u2013 On 31 July 2014, [[RTL T\u00e9l\u00e9 L\u00ebtzebuerg]] confirmed that Luxembourg would not be returning to the contest in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|first=Sanjay|last=Jiandani|title=Luxembourg: RTL will not return to Eurovision in 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/85926/luxembourg-rtl-will-return-eurovision-2015/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=30 July 2014|date=30 July 2014}}</ref> However, it was reported on 26 October 2014 that the country's Minister of Culture, Maggy Nagel, expressed her desire for the country to return to the contest.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bettega|first1=Tania|url=http://www.wort.lu/en/culture/during-eurovision-gala-night-culture-minister-agrees-to-luxembourg-s-eurovision-return-544cee53b9b398870807f45a|title=Culture Minister agrees to Luxembourg's Eurovision return|website=wort.lu|publisher=Luxemburger Wort|date=26 October 2014|accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fiden|first1=Mustafa|title=Luxembourger culture minister agrees to the country's return|url=http://eurovoix.com/2014/10/26/luxembourger-culture-minister-agrees-to-the-countrys-return/|website=eurovoix.com|publisher=Eurovoix|accessdate=26 October 2014|date=26 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026202747/http://eurovoix.com/2014/10/26/luxembourger-culture-minister-agrees-to-the-countrys-return/|archivedate=26 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=luxembourg_to_return_to_eurovision|title=Luxembourg plans return to Eurovision?|publisher=Eurovision Song Contest|date=27 October 2014|accessdate=27 October 2014}}</ref> This was later confirmed by Nagel to be a \"misunderstanding\" and that the country would not be returning.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bettega|first1=Tania|url=http://www.wort.lu/en/culture/minister-of-culture-denial-luxembourg-s-eurovision-return-is-misunderstanding-544f6df8b9b3988708080123|title=Luxembourg's Eurovision return is \"misunderstanding\"|website=wort.lu|publisher=Luxemburger Wort|date=28 October 2014|accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref> A collaboration with San Marino had been proposed by the broadcaster [[SMtv San Marino|SMRTV]] and singer [[Thierry Mersch]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bettega|first1=Tania|url=http://www.wort.lu/en/culture/just-50-000-euros-needed-luxembourg-could-return-to-eurovision-in-san-marino-collaboration-544fbb57b9b3988708080169|title=Luxembourg could return to Eurovision in San Marino collaboration|website=wort.lu|publisher=Luxemburger Wort|date=28 October 2014|accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Granger|first=Anthony|url=http://eurovoix.com/2014/10/28/luxembourg-joint-participation-with-san-marino/|title=Luxembourg: Joint Participation With San Marino?|website=eurovoix.com|publisher=Eurovoix|accessdate=28 October 2014|date=28 October 2014}}</ref> but later SMRTV clarified that there have only been talks between the two countries and the broadcaster is evaluating other proposals.<ref>{{cite web|website=smtvsanmarino.sm|publisher=SMRTV|url=http://www.smtvsanmarino.sm/attualita/2014/10/29/eurovision-song-contest-rumors-partecipazione-precisazione-rtv|title=Eurovision Song Contest: rumors sulla partecipazione, la precisazione di Rtv|accessdate=29 October 2014|date=29 October 2014|language=Italian|trans-title=Eurovision Song Contest: rumors on the participation, the clarification of Rtv}}</ref> However, on 24 November 2014, it was announced that Mersch had failed to raise the necessary funds in time for the project to move forward.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bettega|first1=Tania|url=http://www.wort.lu/en/culture/esc-2015-no-eurovision-deal-for-luxembourg-and-san-marino-547356040c88b46a8ce40a08|title=No Eurovision deal for Luxembourg and San Marino|website=wort.lu|publisher=Luxemburger Wort|date=24 November 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Monaco}} \u2013 Monegasque broadcaster [[T\u00e9l\u00e9 Monte Carlo]] (TMC) confirmed on 20 June 2014 that Monaco would not return to the contest in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Monaco: TMC will not be returning in Eurovision 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/85056/monaco-tmc-will-return-eurovision-2015/|accessdate=20 June 2014|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|date=20 June 2014|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday}}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Morocco}} \u2013 Moroccan broadcaster [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Nationale de Radiodiffusion et de T\u00e9l\u00e9vision]] (SNRT) confirmed on 31 October 2014 that Morocco would not return to the contest in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Morocco: SNRT will not return to Eurovision in 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/86637/morocco-snrt/|accessdate=31 October 2014|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|date=31 October 2014|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday}}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Slovakia}} \u2013 On 26 August 2014, [[Radio and Television Slovakia]] (RTVS) announced that Slovakia would not return to the contest in 2015 because of financial restrictions and an incompatibility between the contest format and the programming goals of the broadcaster.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|url=http://esctoday.com/86385/slovakia/|title=Slovakia: RTVS will not return to Eurovision in 2015|website=esctoday.com|publisher=EscToday|date=26 August 2014|accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Turkey}} \u2013 Though the [[Turkish Radio and Television Corporation]] (TRT) announced that Turkey would not be participating in the {{Escyr|2014|2014 contest}} for the second year in a row, it was later reported that a return in the 2015 Contest could be possible with Eurovision event supervisor Sietse Bakker tweeting about the possibility of the country's return.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eurovisiontimes.wordpress.com/2013/11/09/will-turkey-return-in-2015/|title=Will Turkey Return in 2015?|work=Eurovision Times|author=Hulluna|accessdate=30 June 2014|date=9 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eurovisiontimes.wordpress.com/2014/02/14/eurovision-2015-turkey-to-return/|title=Eurovision 2015: Turkey to Return?|work=Eurovision Times|author=Hulluna|accessdate=30 June 2014|date=14 February 2014}}</ref> In late August 2014, it was reported that international public relations officer for TRT, Ya\u011fmur T\u00fcz\u00fcn, stated that Turkey would not be returning to the contest in 2015 and that TRT currently has no plans to return to the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eurovisionireland.net/2014/08/25/exclusive-trt-confirm-to-eurovision-ireland-that-turkey-will-not-attend-eurovision-2015/|title=Exclusive: TRT confirm to Eurovision Ireland that Turkey will not attend Eurovision 2015|website=eurovisionireland.net|publisher=Eurovision Ireland|last=Mulhall|first=Garrett|date=25 August 2014|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/86392/turkey-trt-plans-return-eurovision-2015/|title=Turkey: TRT has no plans to return to Eurovision in 2015|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|date=26 August 2014|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> The non-participation was further confirmed on 5 September 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/86670/turkey-trt-confirms-return-eurovision-2015/|title=Turkey: TRT confirms no return to Eurovision in 2015|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|date=5 September 2014|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref> \n* {{Esc|Ukraine}} \u2013 On 19 September 2014, Ukrainian broadcaster [[National Television Company of Ukraine]] (NTU) announced that Ukraine would not be participating in the contest because of financial reasons and the ongoing [[War in Donbass|armed conflict]] in the country.<ref name=\"Ukraine1\">{{cite web|script-title=uk:\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0430 \u0431\u0435\u0440\u0435 \u0442\u0430\u0439\u043c-\u0430\u0443\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0440\u0456\u043a \u0443 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441\u0456 \u0404\u0432\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f|url=http://1tv.com.ua/uk/about/news/2014/09/19/59170|website=1tv.com.ua|publisher=[[National Television Company of Ukraine|NTU]]|accessdate=27 September 2014|language=Ukrainian|date=19 September 2014|trans-title=Ukraine takes time out for a year in Eurovision|last=Alasania|first=Zurab}}</ref><ref name=\"Ukraine2\">{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/86848/ukraine-ntu-will-not-participate-in-eurovision-2015/|title=Ukraine: NTU will not participate in Eurovision 2015|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|date=19 September 2014|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref> On 16 September 2015, it was announced that Ukraine would return to the contest in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|title=Ukraine: NTU confirms participation in Eurovision 2016|url=http://esctoday.com/105150/ukraine-ntu-confirms-participation-in-eurovision-2016/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|date=16 September 2015|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Require active EBU membership ===\n* {{Esc|Liechtenstein}} \u2013 The Liechtenstein broadcaster [[1FLTV]] suspended its plans to join the EBU because of lack of funding.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|title=Liechtentestein: 1 FL TV will not debut in Eurovision 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/85870/liechtentestein-1-fl-tv-will-debut-eurovision-2015/|date=28 July 2014 |publisher=ESCToday.com|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Incidents==\n===Anti-booing technology===\n[[File:20150512 ESC 2015 Polina Gagarina 4768.jpg|thumb|Polina Gagarina in 2015]]\nDuring the results, loud boos could be heard whenever Russia was mentioned or the country received one of the top three high points.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/eurovision/eurovision-2015-russia-booed-despite-song-contests-best-efforts-to-put-music-over-politics-10272901.html|title=Eurovision 2015: Russia booed despite song contest's best efforts to put 'music over politics'|work=The Independent|accessdate=24 May 2015}}</ref> The Russian entrant [[Polina Gagarina]] could be seen crying in the green room during the voting procedure, and this was reported by various media to have occurred as a result of the [[booing]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eurovisionni.wordpress.com/2015/05/24/russias-polina-in-tears-after-she-is-booed/|title=Russia\u2019s Polina in Tears After She is Booed|last=nickelhatton|date=2015-05-24|website=Eurovision NI|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> During a break in the countries' reporting of their votes, when the running total showed Russia leading, Eurovision 2014 winner Conchita Wurst announced to Gagarina, \"You gave an amazing performance, and you deserve to be in the lead.\"<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/> The Executive Supervisor of ESC, [[Jon Ola Sand]], urged that Eurovision should be a \"friendly battlefield....not a political battleground\",<ref name=\"eurovision.tv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=vienna_stage_is_100_recyclable|title=Vienna stage is 100% recyclable|work=Gordon Roxburgh, Eurovision Song Contest|accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref> and presenter Alice Tumler reminded the audience that \"Our motto is 'Building Bridges', and music should stand over politics tonight...\". The organisers had anticipated such reactions, and had prepared and installed '[[active noise control|anti-booing technology]]' which was deployed for the first time in Eurovision broadcasting history.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Aubusson|first1=Kate|title=Anti-booing technology deployed to protect Russian contestant|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/eurovision-2015-antibooing-technology-deployed-to-protect-russian-contestant-20150524-gh8lni.html|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=26 May 2015|date=24 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Smoke machine malfunction===\nDuring the performance of Georgia in the grand final, a smoke machine malfunctioned, causing the Georgian entrant [[Nina Sublatti]] to disappear temporarily on the stage in a cloud of grey smoke.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fuster|first1=Luis|title=Nina Sublatti fans angry over smoke machine fail|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2015/05/24/georgia-nina-sublatti-smoke-machine/96434/|website=wiwibloggs.com|publisher=Wiwibloggs|accessdate=24 May 2015|date=24 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Macedonia and Montenegro jury results excluded===\nThe jury votes from Macedonia and Montenegro in the final were not included, in accordance to the rulebook of the ESC. The rules for voting indicate that votes must be 50% jurors, 50% televoting, but Macedonia's and Montenegro's voting was 100% televoting. The final result of the contest was not affected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/eurovision-2015-votes-disqualified-montenegro-5751425|title=Eurovision 2015 votes DISQUALIFIED: Montenegro and Macedonia's results excluded after irregularities with voting ratio|author=Carl Greenwood|date=23 May 2015|work=mirror|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/live/entertainment-arts-32851414|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2015: As it happened \u2013 BBC News|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Other awards ==\nThe Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards, the OGAE voting poll and the Barbara Dex Awards are awards that were contested by the entries competing at the Eurovision Song Contest 2015, in addition to the main winner's trophy.\n\n=== Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards ===\n{{further|Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards}}\nThe Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards were first handed out during the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2002]] in [[Tallinn, Estonia]], honouring the best competing songs in the final. Founded by [[Christer Bj\u00f6rkman]] ([[Sweden]]'s representative in the [[1992 Eurovision Song Contest]] and the current Head of Delegation for Sweden) and Richard Herrey (a member of the [[Herreys]] and the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1984]] winner from Sweden), the awards are named after the creator of the annual competition, [[Marcel Bezen\u00e7on]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Award \u2013 an introduction|url=http://poplight.zitiz.se/marcelbezenconaward/en|publisher=Poplight.se|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017033001/http://poplight.zitiz.se/marcelbezenconaward/en |archivedate=17 October 2013|accessdate=15 July 2012}}</ref> The awards were divided into three categories: Press Award, Artistic Award, and Composer Award. The winners were revealed shortly before the final on 23 May.<ref>{{cite web|title=ESC\u201915: Marcel Bezen\u00e7on Awards Revealed|url=http://eurovoix.com/2015/05/23/esc15-marcel-bezencon-awards-revealed/|accessdate=23 May 2015|last=Granger|first=Anthony}}</ref>\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n! Category\n! Country\n! Song\n! Performer(s)\n! Composer(s)\n|-\n| Artistic Award\n|  {{Esc|Sweden|y=2015}}\n|\"[[Heroes (M\u00e5ns Zelmerl\u00f6w song)|Heroes]]\"\n|  [[M\u00e5ns Zelmerl\u00f6w]]\n|[[Anton Malmberg H\u00e5rd af Segerstad]], [[Joy Deb]], [[Linnea Deb]]\n|-\n| Composer Award\n|  {{Esc|Norway|y=2015}}\n|\"[[A Monster Like Me]]\"\n|  [[Kjetil M\u00f8rland|M\u00f8rland]] & [[Debrah Scarlett]]\n|Kjetil M\u00f8rland\n|-\n| Press Award\n|  {{Esc|Italy|y=2015}}\n|\"[[Grande amore]]\"\n|  [[Il Volo]]\n|Francesco Boccia, Ciro Esposito\n|-\n|}\n\n=== OGAE ===\n{{further|OGAE}}\nOrganisation G\u00e9n\u00e9rale des Amateurs de l'Eurovision (more commonly known as OGAE) is an international organisation that was founded in 1984 in [[Savonlinna]], [[Finland]] by Jari-Pekka Koikkalainen.<ref name=\"OGAE Clubs\">{{cite web|title=Eurovision Fanclub Network|url=http://www.ogae.net/|website=ogae.net|publisher=OGAE|author=[[OGAE]]|date=15 June 2012|accessdate=15 June 2012}}</ref> The organisation consists of a network of over 40 Eurovision Song Contest fan clubs across Europe and beyond, and is a [[Non-governmental organization|non-governmental]], [[Non-politics|non-political]], and non-profit company.<ref name=Members>{{cite web|url=http://www.euroviisuklubi.fi/index.php?option=com_content&view=section&id=8&Itemid=41|title=Klubi-info: Mik\u00e4 ihmeen OGAE?|publisher=OGAE Finland|accessdate=17 June 2012|date=5 June 2012|language=Finnish|trans-title=The club info: What on Earth is OGAE?}}</ref> In what has become an annual tradition for the OGAE fan clubs, a voting poll ran from 1 May 2015 and ended on 10 May 2015, allowing members from forty clubs to vote for their favourite songs of the 2015 contest.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Weaver|first1=Jessica|title=OGAE Poll 2015: Coming this Friday!|url=http://esctoday.com/100899/ogae-poll-2015-coming-this-friday/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=30 April 2015|date=28 April 2015}}</ref> The table below shows the top five overall results, after votes from forty-one OGAE clubs had been cast.<ref name=\"OGAE Poll 2015\">{{cite document|author1=OGAE International|title=OGAE International ESC Poll 2015|publisher=Google Docs|date=30 April 2015|url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1vVfyi2DhmZ17FxOlXlenMHJMTJ7tUpDnkne7T2UwVFY/edit#gid=0|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n<!-- DON'T EXPAND THIS TABLE ANY FURTHER THAN THE TOP 5 RESULTS -->\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n! Country\n! Performer(s)\n! Song\n! OGAE result<ref name=\"OGAE Poll 2015\"/>\n|- style=\"background:gold;\"\n| {{Esc|Italy|y=2015}}\n| Il Volo\n| \"Grande amore\"\n| 367\n|- style=\"background:silver;\"\n| {{Esc|Sweden|y=2015}}\n| M\u00e5ns Zelmerl\u00f6w\n| \"Heroes\"\n| 338\n|- style=\"background:#c96;\"\n| {{Esc|Estonia|y=2015}}\n| Elina Born & Stig R\u00e4sta\n| \"Goodbye to Yesterday\"\n| 274\n|-\n| {{Esc|Norway|y=2015}}\n| M\u00f8rland & Debrah Scarlett\n| \"A Monster Like Me\"\n| 243\n|-\n| {{Esc|Slovenia|y=2015}}\n| Maraaya\n| \"Here for You\"\n| 228\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Barbara Dex Award ===\n{{further|Barbara Dex Award}}\nThe Barbara Dex Award, annually awarded by the fan website House of Eurovision, is a humorous award given to the worst dressed artist each year in the contest. It is named after the Belgian artist, [[Barbara Dex]], who came last in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1993|1993 contest]], in which she wore a dress she designed herself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurovisionhouse.nl/bdaward.php |title=Barbara Dex Award |last=Thillo |first=Edwin |publisher=Eurovision House |accessdate=24 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826110418/http://www.eurovisionhouse.nl/bdaward.php |archivedate=26 August 2014 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n! Place<ref name=\"Barbara Dex Award 2015\">{{cite web|last1=Roxburgh|first1=Gordon|title=Trijntje Oosterhuis wins the Barbara Dex Award|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=trijntje_oosterhuis_wins_the_barbara_dex_award|publisher=Eurovision Song Contest|accessdate=7 June 2015|date=7 June 2015}}</ref>\n! Country<ref name=\"Barbara Dex Award 2015\"/>\n! Performer(s)<ref name=\"Barbara Dex Award 2015\"/>\n! Votes<ref name=\"Barbara Dex Award 2015\"/>\n|- style=\"background:gold;\"\n| 1\n| {{Esc|Netherlands|y=2015}}\n| [[Trijntje Oosterhuis]]\n| 1,324\n|- style=\"background:silver;\"\n| 2\n| {{Esc|Serbia|y=2015}}\n| [[Bojana Stamenov]]\n| 605\n|- style=\"background:#c96;\"\n| 3\n| {{Esc|United Kingdom|y=2015}}\n| [[Electro Velvet]]\n| 397\n|-\n| 4\n| {{Esc|Albania|y=2015}}\n| [[Elhaida Dani]]\n| 263\n|-\n| 5\n| {{Esc|Romania|y=2015}}\n| [[Voltaj]]\n| 237\n|-\n|}\n\n== International broadcasts and voting ==\nIt was reported by the EBU that the 2015 Contest was viewed by a worldwide television audience of a record breaking 197 million viewers,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Storvik-Green|first1=Simon|title=Nearly 200 million people watch Eurovision 2015|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=nearly_200_million_people_watch_eurovision_2015|publisher=Eurovision Song Contest|accessdate=8 June 2015|date=3 June 2015}}</ref> beating the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014#International broadcasts and voting|2014 record]] which was viewed by 195 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=eurovision_song_contest_2014_reaches_195_million_worldwide |title=Eurovision Song Contest 2014 reaches 195 million worldwide |publisher=Eurovision Song Contest |last=Bakker |first=Sietse |date=4 June 2014 |accessdate=4 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Voting and spokespersons ===\nThe voting order was revealed the morning of the final, and for the only time in Eurovision history to date, the names of all the spokespersons were displayed onscreen. However, because of technical problems in some countries the final voting order was the following:<ref name=\"Voting Issues\">{{cite web|last1=Roxburgh|first1=Gordon|title=\"Good evening Vienna\" \u2013 Voting order revealed|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=good_evening_vienna_-_voting_order_revealed|publisher=Eurovision Song Contest|accessdate=23 May 2015|date=23 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150524061128/https://eurovision.tv/page/news?id=good_evening_vienna_-_voting_order_revealed|archive-date=24 May 2015}}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n# {{Esc|Montenegro}} \u2013 [[Andrea Demirovi\u0107]] <small>(Montenegrin representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2009|2009 Contest]])</small>\n# {{Esc|Malta}} \u2013 [[Julie Zahra]] <small>(Maltese representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2004|2004 Contest]] along with [[Ludwig Galea]])</small>\n# {{Esc|Finland}} \u2013 [[Krista Siegfrids]] <small>(Finnish representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2013|2013 Contest]])</small>\n# {{Esc|Greece}} \u2013 [[Helena Paparizou]] <small>(Greek representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2001|2001 Contest]] as part of [[Antique (duo)|Antique]], winner of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2005|2005 Contest]])</small>\n# {{Esc|Romania}} \u2013 Sonia Argint Ionescu\n# {{Esc|Belarus}} \u2013 [[Teo (singer)|Teo]] <small>(Belarusian representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014 Contest]])</small>\n# {{Esc|Albania}} \u2013 [[Andri Xhahu]]\n# {{Esc|Moldova}} \u2013 Olivia Furtun\u0103\n# {{Esc|Azerbaijan}} \u2013 Tural Asadov\n# {{Esc|Latvia}} \u2013 Markus Riva\n# {{Esc|Serbia}} \u2013 Maja Nikoli\u0107\n# {{Esc|Denmark}} \u2013 [[Basim (singer)|Basim]] <small>(Danish representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014 Contest]])</small>\n# {{Esc|Switzerland}} \u2013 [[Laetitia Guarino]]\n# {{Esc|Belgium}} \u2013 Walid\n# {{Esc|France}} \u2013 [[Virginie Guilhaume]]\n# {{Esc|Armenia}} \u2013 Lilit Muradyan\n# {{Esc|Ireland}} \u2013 [[Nicky Byrne]] <small>(Irish representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2016|2016 Contest]])</small>\n# {{Esc|Sweden}} \u2013 [[Mariette Hansson]]\n# {{Esc|Germany}} \u2013 [[Barbara Sch\u00f6neberger]]\n# {{Esc|Australia}} \u2013 [[Lee Lin Chin]]\n# {{Esc|Czech Republic}} \u2013 Daniela P\u00edsa\u0159ovicov\u00e1\n# {{Esc|Spain}} \u2013 Lara Siscar\n# {{Esc|Austria}} \u2013 [[Katharina Bellowitsch|Kati Bellowitsch]]\n# {{Esc|Macedonia}} \u2013 Marko Mark\n# {{Esc|Slovenia}} \u2013 [[Tinkara Kova\u010d]] <small>(Slovene representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014 Contest]])</small>\n# {{Esc|Hungary}} \u2013 [[Csilla Tat\u00e1r]]\n# {{Esc|United Kingdom}} \u2013 [[Nigella Lawson]]\n# {{Esc|Lithuania}} \u2013 Ugn\u0117 Galadauskait\u0117\n# {{Esc|Netherlands}} \u2013 [[Edsilia Rombley]] <small> (Dutch representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1998|1998]] and [[Eurovision Song Contest 2007|2007 Contests]])</small>\n# {{Esc|Poland}} \u2013 Ola Ciupa\n# {{Esc|Israel}} \u2013 Ofer Nachshon\n# {{Esc|Russia}} \u2013 Dmitry Shepelev <small>(Green room host of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2009|2009 Contest]])</small>\n# {{Esc|San Marino}} \u2013 [[Valentina Monetta]] <small>(Sammarinese representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 2013|2013]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014]], and [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017|2017 Contests]])</small>\n# {{Esc|Italy}} \u2013 Federico Russo\n# {{Esc|Iceland}} \u2013 Sigr\u00ed\u00f0ur Halld\u00f3rsd\u00f3ttir\n# {{Esc|Cyprus}} \u2013 Loukas Hamatsos\n# {{Esc|Norway}} \u2013 [[Margrethe R\u00f8ed]]\n# {{Esc|Portugal}} \u2013 [[Suzy (singer)|Suzy]] <small> (Portuguese representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014 Contest]])</small>{{ref|j|1}}\n# {{Esc|Estonia}} \u2013 [[Tanja Mihhailova|Tanja]] <small>(Estonian representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014 Contest]])</small>{{ref|j|1}}\n# {{Esc|Georgia}} \u2013 Natia Bunturi{{ref|j|1}}\n\n{{div col end}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n;Notes\n<small>1.{{note|j}} Portugal, Estonia and Georgia were originally scheduled to announce their votes as the 5th, 13th and 30th countries, respectively, but instead voted 38th, 39th and 40th, respectively, after all the other countries announced their votes. The reason for this was technical difficulties in the minutes running up to the voting presentation.</small><ref name=\"Voting Issues\"/>\n\n=== Commentators ===\nMost countries sent commentators to Vienna or commentated from their own country, in order to add insight to the participants and, if necessary, the provision of voting information.\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* {{flagicon|Albania}} Albania&nbsp;\u2013 [[Andri Xhahu]] ([[RTSH]], all shows){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n* {{flagicon|Armenia}} Armenia&nbsp;\u2013 [[Aram Mp3]] and Erik Antaranyan ([[AMPTV]], first semi-final); Vahe Khanamiryan and Hermine Stepanyan ([[AMPTV]], second semi-final); [[Avet Barseghyan]] and Arevik Udumyan ([[AMPTV]], final){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n* {{flagicon|Australia}} Australia&nbsp;\u2013 [[Julia Zemiro]] and [[Sam Pang]] ([[SBS One]], all shows)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Knox|first1=David|title=SBS 2015: TV Highlights|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2014/11/sbs-2015-highlights-poh-go-back-food-and-drama.html|website=tvtonight.com.au|publisher=TV Tonight|accessdate=14 November 2014|date=14 November 2014|quote=Eurovision has become one of the most popular television events in Australia. Next year is the 60th anniversary of Eurovision and with the official theme \u2018Building Bridges\u2019 already announced by host country Austria, SBS can reveal we have our Eurovision engineers Julia Zemiro and Sam Pang already working on how we can build a bridge to Vienna and join the Eurovision Song Contest in 2015.}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Austria}} Austria&nbsp;\u2013 [[Andi Knoll]] ([[ORF eins]], all shows)\n* {{flagicon|Azerbaijan}} Azerbaijan&nbsp;\u2013 Kamran Guliyev ([[\u0130TV]] and [[\u0130TV]] Radio, all shows)<ref>{{cite web|last=Vranis|first=Michalis|title=Big Poll Commentators: Here are the Semi-final 1 results|url=http://esctoday.com/104040/big-poll-commentators-here-are-the-semi-final-1-results/|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=19 May 2015|date=23 May 2015}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Belarus}} Belarus&nbsp;\u2013 Evgeny Perlin ([[Belarus-1]] and [[Belarus 24|Belarus-24]], all shows)<ref name=BRTC>{{cite web|url=http://www.belta.by/ru/all_news/culture/Belorusskaja-delegatsija-otpravitsja-na-konkurs-pesni-Evrovidenie-10-maja_i_704399.html |script-title=ru:\u0411\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u043e\u0442\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441 \u043f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438 \"\u0415\u0432\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\" 10 \u043c\u0430\u044f |website=belta.by |publisher=[[Belarusian Telegraph Agency]] |date=6 May 2015 |accessdate=8 May 2015 |language=Russian |trans-title=The Belarusian delegation will go to the contest \"Eurovision\" 10 May |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514053223/http://www.belta.by/ru/all_news/culture/Belorusskaja-delegatsija-otpravitsja-na-konkurs-pesni-Evrovidenie-10-maja_i_704399.html |archivedate=14 May 2015  }}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Belgium}} Belgium&nbsp;\u2013 ''Dutch'': [[Peter Van de Veire]] and Eva Daeleman ([[\u00e9\u00e9n]] and [[Radio 2 (Belgium)|Radio 2]], all shows);<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deredactie.be/cm/vrtnieuws/cultuur%2Ben%2Bmedia/media/1.2304954|publisher=deredactie.be|title=Van de Veire en Daeleman leveren commentaar bij Songfestival|language=Dutch|trans-title=Van de Veire and Daeleman commentate at Eurovision.|date=15 April 2015|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref> ''French'': Jean-Louis Lahaye and [[Maureen Louys]] ([[La Une]], all shows);<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhnet.be/medias/television/eurovision-60-ans-et-des-changements-54c7cfb735700d75223d74ed|title=Eurovision: 60 ans et des changements|publisher=dhnet.be|date=27 January 2015|accessdate=16 February 2015|language=French|trans-title=Eurovision: 60 years and changing.}}</ref> Olivier Gilain ([[VivaCit\u00e9]], final)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtbf.be/vivacite/emissions_viva-musique?programId=5904|title=RTBF VivaCit\u00e9|publisher=Rtbf.be|date=20 May 2015|accessdate=22 May 2015|language=French|trans-title=RTBF VivaCit\u00e9.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150603033124/http://www.rtbf.be/vivacite/emissions_viva-musique?programId=5904|archive-date=3 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Cyprus}} Cyprus&nbsp;\u2013 Melina Karageorgiou ([[Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation|RIK 1]], [[Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation|RIK SAT]], [[Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation|RIK HD]] and [[Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation|Trito Programma]], all shows)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riknews.com.cy/index.php/news/to-rik-en-drasei/item/16402-eurovision-me-symmetoxi-tis-elladas-o-1os-imitelikos|title=\u039c\u03b5 \u03c3\u03c5\u03bc\u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03bf\u03c7\u03ae \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1\u03c2 \u03bf 1\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b7\u03bc\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2|website=riknews.com|publisher=[[Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=15 May 2015|accessdate=15 May 2015|language=Greek|trans-title=With participation of Greece the first semi-final}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Czech Republic}} Czech Republic&n