ted States]]\n[[Category:Drone strikes in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Iran\u2013United States military relations]]\n[[Category:Iran\u2013United States proxy conflict]]\n[[Category:Iraq\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Military assassinations]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving the United States]]\n[[Category:Presidency of Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Qasem Soleimani]]\n[[Category:Targeted killing in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Trump administration controversies]]\n", "name_user": "RopeTricks", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIraqi response", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Baghdad_International_Airport_airstrike"}
{"title_page": "Defence Health Services (Namibia)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Defence Health Services\n| image = \n| caption = \n| dates = \n| country = [[Namibia]]\n| allegiance =\n| branch =\n| type = \n| role = \n| size = \n| command_structure = [[Namibia Defence Force]]\n| garrison = \n| garrison_label = \n| nickname = \n| colors = \n| colors_label = \n| march = \n| start_date = \n| engagements = \n| current_commander = [[Brigadier General]] Sophia Ndeitunga\n| current_commander_label = Chief of Staff\n| ceremonial_chief = \n| ceremonial_chief_label = <!-- Insignia -->\n}}\n\n\nThe '''Defence Health Service''' Directorate is the branch of the [[Namibian Defence Force]] responsible for medical facilities and the training and deployment of all medical personnel within the force. \n\nIt is a significant actor in the effort to control [[HIV/AIDS]] within the NDF.\n\n==History==\n\n===Formations===\n\n====Mobile Military Health Formation====\n*Mobile Field Hospital<ref>https://www.thenamibian.mobi/197902/archive-read/Mobile-field-hospital-set-up-at-airport</ref><ref>https://economist.com.na/9565/health/armed-forces-receive-field-hospital/</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=5&v=_-t4dgaB_TM&feature=emb_logo</ref>\n\n====Tertiary Military Health Formation====\n* Grootfontein Military Hospital\n* Peter Mueshihange Military Center\n\n====Military Health Training Formation====\n* Medical Training Wing\n\n== Leadership ==\n1999- Incubent Brigadier General Sophia Ndeitunga\n\n==See also==\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Military of Namibia]]\n[[Category:Armies by country|Namibia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Defence Health Services\n| image = \n| caption = \n| dates = \n| country = [[Namibia]]\n| allegiance =\n| branch =\n| type = \n| role = \n| size = \n| command_structure = [[Namibia Defence Force]]\n| garrison = \n| garrison_label = \n| nickname = \n| colors = \n| colors_label = \n| march = \n| start_date = \n| engagements = \n| current_commander = [[Brigadier General]] Sophia Ndeitunga\n| current_commander_label = Chief of Staff\n| ceremonial_chief = \n| ceremonial_chief_label = <!-- Insignia -->\n}}\n\n\nThe '''Defence Health Service''' Directorate is the branch of the [[Namibian Defence Force]] responsible for medical facilities and the training and deployment of all medical personnel within the force. \n\nIt is a significant actor in the effort to control [[HIV/AIDS]] within the NDF.\n\n==History==\n\n===Formations===\n\n====Mobile Military Health Formation====\n*Mobile Field Hospital<ref>https://www.thenamibian.mobi/197902/archive-read/Mobile-field-hospital-set-up-at-airport</ref><ref>https://economist.com.na/9565/health/armed-forces-receive-field-hospital/</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=5&v=_-t4dgaB_TM&feature=emb_logo</ref>\n\n====Tertiary Military Health Formation====\n* Grootfontein Military Hospital\n* Peter Mueshihange Military Center\n\n====Military Health Training Formation====\n* Medical Training Wing\n\n== Leadership ==\n\n{{Post-end}}\n\n==See also==\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Military of Namibia]]\n[[Category:Armies by country|Namibia]]\n", "name_user": "ViceAdmiral", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLeadership", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Defence_Health_Services_(Namibia)"}
{"title_page": "Gene Simmons", "text_new": "{{about|the rock singer and musician|the actress|Jean Simmons|the rockabilly singer|Jumpin' Gene Simmons|the mass murderer|Ronald Gene Simmons}}\n{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Gene Simmons\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Gene Simmons 2012.jpg\n| caption          = Simmons in October 2012\n| birth_name       = Chaim Witz\n| alias            = {{hlist|The Demon|The God of Thunder|Dr. Love|Reginald Van Helsing}}\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1949|8|25}}\n| birth_place      = [[Tirat Carmel]], Israel\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Hard rock]]|[[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Musician|singer-songwriter|record producer|actor|entrepreneur|television personality}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|bass guitar}}<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| years_active     = 1970\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Kiss (band)|Kiss]]|[[Wicked Lester]]}}\n| website          = {{URL|genesimmons.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Gene Klein''' (born '''Chaim Witz'''{{efn|{{lang-he|\u05d7\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05d9\u05e5}}, {{IPA-he|\u03c7a\u02c8im \u02c8vits|pron}}.}} on August 25, 1949), known professionally as '''Gene Simmons''', is an American musician, singer, songwriter, record producer, entrepreneur, actor, author and television personality. Also known by his stage persona '''The Demon''', he is the bassist and co-lead singer of [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]], the rock band he co-founded with lead singer and rhythm guitarist [[Paul Stanley]] in the early 1970s. Simmons possesses a baritone singing voice which contrasts with [[Paul Stanley]] and [[Peter Criss]]' tenor voices.\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Early life===\nSimmons was born as Chaim Witz on August 25, 1949 at [[Rambam Hospital]] in [[Haifa]], [[Israel]] to Jewish emigrants from Hungary. His mother, Florence Klein (originally Fl\u00f3ra Kov\u00e1cs), was born in [[J\u00e1nd]], [[Hungarian People's Republic|Hungary]], and survived internment in [[Nazi concentration camps]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/arlene-lassin/gene-simmons-mom-the-hologene-simmons-mom-the-holocaust-and-me_b_7082854.html|title=Gene Simmons' Mom, the Holocaust, and Me|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=2015-04-17}}</ref> She and her brother, Larry Klein, were the only members of the family to survive [[the Holocaust]]. His father, Ferenc \"Feri\" Yehiel Witz, was a carpenter. Simmons spent his early childhood in [[Tirat Carmel]], and was raised in a [[Jewish]] household. He practiced playing his guitar for hours on end.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GkEKAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bksDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6424%2C900667|title=KISS army continues to grow|work=The Victoria Advocate|date=October 4, 1998|accessdate=August 9, 2015|author=Martin, Dale|page=10D}}</ref> He has said that his family was \"dirt poor,\" scraping by on rationed bread and milk.<ref name=haaretz>{{cite web|last=Associated|first=The|url=http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/lead-singer-of-kiss-gene-simmons-slams-israel-boycotters-1.351197|title=Lead singer of Kiss Gene Simmons slams Israel boycotters|work=Haaretz|location=Israel|date=March 22, 2011|accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref> At age seven, he began to pick wild fruit and sell it on roadsides together with a friend.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-32301157 | title=The rock star who can never be too rich| work=BBC News| date=2015-04-19| last1=Smale| first1=Will}}</ref>\n\nAt age eight, he immigrated to the United States with his mother and settled in New York City. His father remained in Israel, where he had one other son and three daughters. In the United States, Simmons changed his name to Eugene Klein, adopting his mother's maiden name. At age nine, he briefly attended a Jewish religious school, [[Yeshiva Torah Vodaas]], before transferring to a public school.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/1949-a-hard-rocker-demon-is-born-1.5390524 | title=1949: A Hard Rocker Demon and Good Jewish Boy is Born| newspaper=Haaretz| date=2015-08-25}}</ref> He later attended [[Richmond College (New York City)|Richmond College]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/college-staten-island-cuny |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628044216/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/college-staten-island-cuny |title=College of Staten Island CUNY |website=Times Higher Education (THE) |archivedate=June 28, 2018 |url-status=unfit|date=2018-09-19 }}</ref> and [[Sullivan County Community College]], both in New York, and chose a stage name in tribute to the rockabilly singer [[Jumpin' Gene Simmons]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://JewishVirtualLibrary.org/gene-simmons |title=Gene Simmons |encyclopedia=Jewish Virtual Library |accessdate=February 17, 2019}}</ref> Before his musical career began, Klein/Simmons worked a variety of jobs in the city. An \"excellent typist\", he served as an assistant to an editor of the [[fashion magazine]] ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', and also spent several months as a sixth grade instructor on the [[Upper West Side]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Lakeland Ledger|date=June 4, 1978|title=Gene Simmons Was Sixth Grade Teacher|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1346&dat=19780604&id=sJJNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yvoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5422,1350574|first=Barbara|last=Lewis}}</ref>\n\n[[The Beatles]] had a significant influence on Simmons. \"There is no way I'd be doing what I do now if it wasn't for the Beatles. I was watching ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'' and I saw them. Those skinny little boys, kind of androgynous, with long hair like girls. It blew me away that these four boys [from] the middle of nowhere could make that music.\"<ref>Crandall, Bill. [http://www.cbsnews.com/news/10-musicians-who-saw-the-beatles-standing-there \"10 musicians who saw the Beatles standing there\"], CBS News, February 6, 2014.</ref>\n\n===Kiss===\n[[File:Gene Simmons - Azkena Rock Festival 2010 6.jpg|thumb|right|Gene Simmons as \"The Demon\", 2010]]\nSimmons became involved with his first band, Lynx, then renamed the Missing Links, when he was a teenager. Eventually, he disbanded the band to form the Long Island Sounds, the name being a pun on [[Long Island Sound]]. While he played in these bands, he worked at odd jobs on the side to make more money, including trading used comic books. Simmons attended [[Sullivan County Community College]] in [[Loch Sheldrake, New York|Loch Sheldrake]], New York. He joined a new band, Bullfrog Bheer, and the band recorded a demo, \"Leeta\"; this was later included on the Kiss box set.\n\nSimmons formed the rock band [[Wicked Lester]] in the early 1970s with Stanley Eisen (now known as [[Paul Stanley]]) and recorded one album, which was never released. Dissatisfied with Wicked Lester's sound and look, Simmons and Stanley attempted to fire their band members; they were met with resistance, and they quit Wicked Lester, walking away from their record deal with [[Epic Records]]. They decided to form the \"ultimate rock band\", and started looking for a drummer. Simmons and Stanley found an ad placed by George Peter John Criscuola (known as [[Peter Criss]]) who was playing clubs in [[Brooklyn]] at the time; they joined and started out as a trio.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nDuring this time, Criss and Simmons also appeared on an unreleased album by Captain Sanity together with members from Criss' previous band Chelsea. Paul Frehley (better known as [[Ace Frehley]]) responded to an ad they put in ''[[The Village Voice]]'' for a lead guitar player, and soon joined them. [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] released their self-titled debut album in February 1974. Stanley took on the role of lead performer on stage, while Simmons became the driving force behind what became an extensive [[Kiss merchandising]] [[exclusive right|franchise]]. The eye section of his \"Demon\" makeup with Kiss came from the wing design of comic book character [[Black Bolt]].<ref>KISS bassist Gene Simmons said on an episode of his television show Gene Simmons Family Jewels that he is a big comic book fan, with the bat-like \"wings\" in his \"Demon\" persona costume being modelled after those worn by Black Bolt [http://www.livedash.com/transcript/gene_simmons_family_jewels-(under_the_knife_)/6120/AETVP/Wednesday_November_3_2010/328010/ Gene Simmons Family Jewels \u2013 Under the Knife? \u2013 Wednesday, Nov 3, 2010 \u2013 mReplay Livedash TV Transcript \u2013 Livedash \u2013 Search what is being mentioned across national TV] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009170844/http://www.livedash.com/transcript/gene_simmons_family_jewels-%28under_the_knife_%29/6120/AETVP/Wednesday_November_3_2010/328010/ |date=October 9, 2011 }}. Livedash. Retrieved February 1, 2011.</ref>\n[[File:KISS devil face.svg|thumb|left|120px|Simmons' 'The Demon' make-up]]\n\nIn 1983, when the fame of Kiss was waning, the members took off their trademark make-up and enjoyed a resurgence in popularity that continued into the 1990s. At this time, Peter Criss, the original drummer, was voted out of the band, and a replacement was sought to fill his vacancy. The new drummer was Paul Charles Caravello, who went by the stage name of [[Eric Carr]], and played for Kiss from 1980 until his death in 1991. The band hosted its own fan conventions in 1995, and fan feedback about the original Kiss members reunion influenced the highly successful 1996\u20131997 Alive Worldwide reunion tour. In 1998, the band released ''[[Psycho Circus]]''. Since then, the original line-up has once again dissolved, with [[Tommy Thayer]] replacing [[Ace Frehley]] on lead guitar and [[Eric Singer]] (who performed with Kiss from 1991 through 1996) replacing [[Peter Criss]] on drums.\n\n==Playing style==\nAs well as being the bass player, lead vocal duties are split between Simmons and rhythm guitarist [[Paul Stanley]] among most Kiss songs. Some notable songs featuring Simmons singing lead include \"[[Rock and Roll All Nite]]\", \"[[Deuce (song)|Deuce]]\", \"[[A World Without Heroes]]\", \"[[I Love It Loud]]\", \"[[Calling Dr. Love]]\", \"[[Unholy (song)|Unholy]]\", \"Spit\" (second lead vocals), \"Boomerang\", \"[[You Wanted the Best]]\" (first lead vocals), and \"[[Christine Sixteen]]\", among others. Simmons possesses a baritone vocal range.\n\n===Stage makeup and persona===\nIn addition to playing bass, Simmons is known for his long tongue, which he frequently sticks out while performing, and on stage is known for his demonic figure by spitting fire and vomiting stage blood. \n\nDuring a 1999 interview with ''Rolling Stone'', Simmons was asked about the source and significance of Kiss' stage makeup and personas:\n\n<blockquote>I've always been a fan of [[Americana]], and Americana has always been about imagery, often above content. I think there's nothing wrong with that. The world worships this culture. Most people only think about America in terms of rock & roll, movies and television. Kiss is very all-American, in the sense that our constituency has never had anything in common with critics ... because our power, our lifeblood, our very reason for existence is our fans. Without them, we'd be nothing.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Rolling Stone: The Illustrated Portraits|last=Woodward|first=Fred|publisher=Chronicle Books|year=2000|isbn=978-0811828161|location=|pages=213}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Gene Simmons - Azkena Rock Festival 2010 7.jpg|thumb|right|Gene Simmons [[fire breathing]]]]\nSimmons is a science fiction and [[comic book]] fan and published several [[science fiction fanzines]], among them ''Id'', ''Cosmos'' (which eventually merged with ''Stilletto'' to become ''Cosmos-Stilletto'' and then ''Faun''), ''Tinderbox'', ''Sci-Fi Showcase'', ''Mantis'' and ''Adventure''. He also contributed to other fanzines, among them ''[[BeABohema]]'' and ''Sirruish''.<ref>[http://www.genesimmons.com/news/102008.html \"Gene Simmons: 60s Fanzine Publisher\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130827172606/http://www.genesimmons.com/news/102008.html |date=August 27, 2013 }}, October 2008</ref> By 1977, however, he would write in a [[letter of comment]] to [[Janus (magazine)|''Janus'']], \"I haven't been active [in fandom] for about five years\".<ref>Simmons, Gene. \"Letter\" ''Janus'' 8 (Vol 3, No. 2); Janice Bogstad & [[Jeanne Gomoll]], eds., 1977; p. 15</ref>\n\nSimmons lives in Los Angeles, California with his wife, Canadian former [[Playboy Playmate]] and actress [[Shannon Lee Tweed]]. Although they began dating in 1983, they did not marry until 28 years later.<ref name=mcfliker/> Simmons often joked that he and Tweed were \"happily unmarried\" for over 20 years. He also often stated, \"Marriage is an institution, and I don't want to live in an institution\". Simmons and Tweed wed on October 1, 2011 at the [[Beverly Hills Hotel]].<ref name=mcfliker/><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20533363,00.html|title=Gene Simmons is married|magazine=The People|date=October 1, 2011|accessdate=October 2, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wonderwall.msn.com/entertainment/gene-simmons-and-longtime-girlfriend-marry-1644963.story|title=Gene Simmons and long term girlfriend marry|publisher=MSN \u2013 Wonderwall|date=October 1, 2011|accessdate=October 2, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130129071428/http://wonderwall.msn.com/entertainment/gene-simmons-and-longtime-girlfriend-marry-1644963.story|archivedate=January 29, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> They have two children: a son named [[Nick Simmons|Nick]] (born January 22, 1989) and a daughter named [[Sophie Simmons|Sophie]] (born July 7, 1992). He formerly had [[live-in relationship]]s with [[Cher]] and [[Diana Ross]],<ref name=\"bio\">[http://www.genesimmons.com/bio2.html Biography] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120906204718/http://www.genesimmons.com/bio2.html |date=September 6, 2012 }}. GeneSimmons.com. Retrieved February 1, 2011.</ref> revealing that he fell in love with Ross while dating Cher.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/gene-simmons-fell-for-diana-ross-while-dating-cher/2015/06/01/78e33fc8-081b-11e5-951e-8e15090d64ae_story.html|title=Gene Simmons fell for Diana Ross while dating Cher|last=|first=|date=June 1, 2015|website=The Washington Post|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref> Simmons can speak Hungarian, German, English, Hebrew and some Japanese.<ref name=bio /> Simmons does not drink [[Alcoholic beverage|alcohol]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/gene-simmons-drugs/|title=Gene Simmons Doesn\u2019t Drink or Do Drugs Because of His Mother|last=|first=|date=7 February 2019|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|access-date=3 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Homecoming visit to Israel===\nIn March 2011, Simmons visited his birth country, Israel. He described the trip as a \"life changing experience\". He talked about how he still feels that he is an Israeli: \"I'm Israeli. I'm a stranger in America. I'm an outsider\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Josef|last=Federman|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20110322/ap_en_mu/ml_israel_people_gene_simmons |title=AP Interview: Simmons blasts Israel boycotters |publisher=Yahoo! |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110326171849/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20110322/ap_en_mu/ml_israel_people_gene_simmons |archivedate=March 26, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> While there, Simmons met his half-brother Kobi, and triplet half-sisters Drora, Sharon and Ogenia.<ref>{{cite web|author=Late Night Rocker |url=http://kissmaskwebzine.blogspot.com/2011/03/meet-gene-simmons-brother-and-sisters.html |title=Kiss Mask Webzine: Meet Gene Simmons' Brother and Sisters |publisher=Kissmaskwebzine.blogspot.com |date=March 31, 2011 |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref> Simmons has plans to take Kiss to Israel. He has said that he is an ardent supporter of Israel.<ref>{{cite web|last=Brinn |first=David |url=http://www.jpost.com/VideoArticles/Video/Article.aspx?id=213425 |title=Kiss rocker Gene Simmons back in Israel after 51 years |work=Jerusalem Post |date=March 23, 2011 |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref> At a press conference in Israel, he spoke in both [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] and English.<ref>{{youtube|FhnTbJNH0Wo|Gene Simmons in Israel / \u05d2'\u05d9\u05df \u05e1\u05d9\u05de\u05d5\u05e0\u05e1 \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc}}</ref>\n\n===Political views===\nSimmons was a supporter of the [[foreign policy of the George W. Bush administration]].<ref>[http://www.genesimmons.com/news/082004.html News] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20121208202854/http://www.genesimmons.com/news/082004.html |date=December 8, 2012 }}. GeneSimmons.com. Retrieved February 1, 2011.</ref> He supported the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], writing on his website: \"I'm ashamed to be surrounded by people calling themselves liberal who are, in my opinion, spitting on the graves of brave American soldiers who gave their life to fight a war that wasn't theirs... in a country they've never been to... simply to liberate the people therein\".<ref name=iraq>[http://www.genesimmons.com/news/042003.html News] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20121208143302/http://www.genesimmons.com/news/042003.html |date=December 8, 2012 }}. GeneSimmons.com. Retrieved February 1, 2011.</ref> In a follow-up, Simmons explained his position and wrote about his love and support for the United States: \"I wasn't born here. But I have a love for this country and its people that knows no bounds. I will forever be grateful to America for going into World War II, when it had nothing to gain, in a country that was far away... and rescued my mother from the Nazi German concentration camps. She is alive and I am alive because of America. And, if you have a problem with America, you have a problem with me\".<ref name=iraq/>\n\nDuring the [[2006 Lebanon War]] between Israel and Lebanon, Simmons sent a televised message of support (in both English and Hebrew) to an Israeli soldier seriously wounded in fighting in Lebanon, calling him his \"hero\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Gene Simmons hails Israeli soldier|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/26/AR2006082600502.html|agency=Associated Press|date=August 26, 2006|accessdate=May 12, 2010|work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Simmons said he regretted voting for [[Barack Obama]] and criticized the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|2009 health care reforms]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/click/stories/1012/gene_simmons_knocks_obama.html|work=[[The Politico]]|first=Patrick|last=Gavin|accessdate=December 6, 2010|date=December 6, 2010|title=Gene Simmons Knocks President Obama}}</ref> Following Obama's 2011 speech on the Middle East in which the President called on Israel and the Palestinians to negotiate a settlement \"based on the 1967 lines with mutually agreed swaps\",<ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2011/05/19/remarks-president-middle-east-and-north-africa Remarks by the President on the Middle East and North Africa], Barack Obama, ''[[The White House]]'', May 19, 2011</ref> Simmons told [[CNBC]] that Obama was gravely misguided. \"If you have never been to the moon, you can't issue policy about the moon. For the president to be sitting in Washington D.C. and saying, 'Go back to your '67 borders in Israel' \u2013 how about you live there and try to defend an indefensible border \u2013 nine miles (14 km) wide?\" Simmons also accused the United Nations of being \"the most pathetic body on the face of the earth\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Ben Gedalyahu|first=Tzvi|title=Video of Rock Star Gene Simmons: Obama Doesn\u2019t Have a Clue|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/144384|accessdate=June 1, 2011|newspaper=[[Arutz Sheva|Israel National News]]|date=May 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring his visit to Israel in 2011, he stated that the artists refusing to perform in Israel for political reasons are \"stupid\".<ref>{{cite news|title=\u05d2'\u05d9\u05df \u05e1\u05d9\u05de\u05d5\u05e0\u05e1: \"\u05d4\u05d9\u05d5\u05e6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05d7\u05e8\u05d9\u05de\u05d9 \u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc \u2013 \u05d8\u05d9\u05e4\u05e9\u05d9\u05dd\"|url=http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4046360,00.html|agency=YNet|date=March 23, 2011|accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn an April 2012 interview, Simmons endorsed Republican [[Mitt Romney]] for President: \"America should be in business and it should be run by a businessman.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/kiss-frontman-gene-simmons-voices-support-for-mitt-romney-regrets-voting-for-obama-in-08/ |title=Kiss Frontman Gene Simmons Voices Support For Mitt Romney, Regrets Voting For Obama In '08 |publisher=Mediaite |date=April 3, 2012 |accessdate=April 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, 2015, he attended a [[Friends of the Israel Defense Forces]] gala in Beverly Hills, which raised more than $31 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Star-studded-LA-fundraiser-rakes-in-31-million-for-IDF-432285|title=IN PICTURES: Star-studded LA fundraiser rakes in $31 million for IDF|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy===\nSimmons is a known advocate for ChildFund International's work. He traveled to Zambia during his ''Gene Simmons Family Jewels'' show to visit several of his sponsored children, of whom he has more than 1400.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.childfund.org/articles/KISS-Icon-Gene-Simmons-Meets-Sponsored-Children/|title=KISS Icon Gene Simmons Brightens Lives of Sponsored Children|work=childfund.org|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Simmons said that the trip \"[was] a stark reminder that life doesn't treat everyone the same\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.childfund.org/media/press_releases/ChildFund_Partners_with_Gene_Simmons_Family_Jewels.aspx|title=ChildFund Partners with Gene Simmons Family Jewels|work=childfund.org|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSimmons' family received the MEND Humanitarian Award for their philanthropic efforts and support for [[Mending Kids International]] at the organization's annual gala on November 9, 2013. The award was presented by [[Mel Gibson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/11079-mel-gibson-presents-gene-simmons-with-charity-award|title=Mel Gibson Presents Gene Simmons With Charity Award|work=Look to the Stars|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=2013-11-12}}</ref> In his acceptance speech, Simmons spoke of his own difficult childhood in Israel in a bullet-riddled house. He recalled his mother's excitement when they received a [[CARE (relief agency)|CARE]] box one day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/mending-kids-international-honors-gene-simmons-shannon-tweed-simmons-nick-simmons-and-sophie-simmons-at-annual-gala-231487311.html|title=Mending Kids International Honors Gene Simmons, Shannon Tweed-Simmons, Nick Simmons And Sophie... -- LOS ANGELES, Nov. 11, 2013 /PRNewswire/ --|author=Mending Kids International|date=November 11, 2013|work=prnewswire.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSimmons helped found \"The Children Matter\", which is a collaborative initiative with the charity MATTER that fights to get kids around the world access to health care.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2017/06/22/gene-simmons-children-matter/l|title=KISS Legend Gene Simmons' Twin Cities Charitable Connection|author=Minnesota CBS local|date=June 22, 2017|work=minnesota.cbslocal.com|accessdate=June 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy===\nOn November 16, 2017, Simmons made an appearance on ''[[Fox & Friends]]'' to promote a new book, but shortly afterward, he burst into a staff meeting uninvited, yanking his shirt and telling jokes. The next day, on November 17, [[Fox News]] announced that Simmons had been banned for life from their program.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Gene Simmons banned from Fox News for life|url=http://theweek.com/speedreads/738078/gene-simmons-reportedly-banned-from-fox-news-life|magazine=The Week|accessdate=November 17, 2017|date=2017-11-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=GENE SIMMONS Apologizes For 'Unintentionally' Offending Members Of FOX Team|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/gene-simmons-apologizes-for-unintentionally-offending-members-of-fox-team/|publisher=blabbermouth.net|accessdate=November 20, 2017|date=2017-11-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Two Women Accuse KISS' Gene Simmons of Sexual Harassment|url=http://www.metalinjection.net/metal-crimes/two-women-accuse-kiss-gene-simmons-of-sexual-harassment|work=Metal Injection|accessdate=November 21, 2017|date=2017-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==Other projects==\nOn August 15, 2013, Simmons, [[Paul Stanley]] and manager [[Doc McGhee]] became a part of the ownership group that created the [[Los Angeles Kiss|LA Kiss]] [[Arena Football League]] team, which played their home games at the [[Honda Center]] in [[Anaheim, California]]. The team has since folded.\n\nHe has his own magazine, ''Gene Simmons Tongue Magazine'', his own label, Simmons Records, and animated series, ''[[My Dad the Rock Star]]''. Simmons Records has released albums by such bands as [[Kobra and the Lotus]], [[Silent Rage (band)|Silent Rage]], [[Gypsy Rose (band)|Gypsy Rose]] and [[House of Lords (band)|House of Lords]] as well as Gene's own solo releases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/label/171919-Simmons-Records|title=Simmons Records|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2019-10-27}}</ref>\n\n=={{anchor|Controversy}}Controversial public statements and image==\n===Promiscuity===\nSimmons has boasted many times about having [[sexual intercourse|bedded]] thousands of women. In 2010, he claimed the tally stood at 5,000 and that he has a [[Instant camera|Polaroid picture]] of each liaison, including the hotel key where it took place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2010/12/20/gene-simmons-kiss-sex-500-women-polaroid-pictures-photos/|title=Gene Simmons- Hard Proof He Banged 5,000 chicks|work=TMZ|date=20 December 2010|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref> A number of years prior, as a guest on [[The Sports Network|TSN]]'s [[Off The Record with Michael Landsberg]], Simmons told fellow guest [[Thea Andrews]] he had slept with 4,500 women, to which Andrews replied she was not interested in being 4,501.<ref name=\"Toronto Star\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/toronto-star/20060825/282789236915535|title=Ten of the best of Landsberg's whackiest (sic) moments|work=Toronto Star|date=25 August 2006|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref> The show's other guest, [[Mark Tewksbury]], offered himself to Simmons instead, to which Simmons declined.<ref name=\"Toronto Star\"/> Tewksbury would state in a 2012 interview with the [[National Post]] that Simmons shook his head at Tewksbury off-camera.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/sports/olympics/20-questions-canadian-olympic-hero-mark-tewksbury-comes-full-circle|title=London Olympics 2012: 20 questions with Canadian Olympic hero Mark Tewksbury|work=National Post|date=10 July 2012|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe told [[Terry Gross]]: \"If you want to welcome me with open arms, I'm afraid you're also going to have to welcome me with open legs\", paraphrasing a lyric from [[the Who]]'s 1981 song \"[[You Better You Bet]]\". Gross replied: \"That's a really obnoxious thing to say\". At the time, Simmons refused to grant permission to NPR to make the interview available online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/TerryGrossInterviewWithGeneSimmons|title=Terry Gross interview with Gene Simmons|work=Internet Archive|accessdate=August 13, 2009}}</ref> However, it appears in print in Gross' book ''All I Did Was Ask'' and unauthorized transcripts are available. NPR re-broadcast part of the interview in August 2007.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=14081542|title=The Unpredictable Gene Simmons|date=31 August 2007|publisher=NPR|accessdate=1 February 2011}}</ref> In a 2014 interview with ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', Simmons noted he was upset over what he perceived as Gross's \"holier-than-thou\" attitude, which included mislabeling his band Kiss as \"the Kiss\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Branch|first1=Chris|title=Gene Simmons Calls NPR's Terry Gross 'Arrogant And Insulting'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/08/12/kiss-gene-simmons-npr-terry-gross_n_5672201.html|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=August 12, 2014|accessdate=August 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Islam comments in Australia===\nIn 2004, during an interview in Melbourne, Australia, while talking about [[Islamic extremism|Islamic extremists]], Simmons described [[Islam]] as a \"vile culture\", saying that Muslim women had to walk behind their husbands and were not allowed to be educated or to own houses. He said: \"They want to come and live right where you live and they think that you're evil.\" Australia's Muslim of the Year [[Susan Carland]] argued that Simmons' stereotyping of Muslims was inaccurate.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/05/14/1084289868279.html \"Outrage as KISS player mouths off on Muslims\"]. ''Sydney Morning Herald'', May 14, 2004</ref> Simmons later clarified his comments on his website, saying he had been talking specifically about Muslim extremists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/gene-simmons-clarifies-muslim-remarks-wbna5086233|title=Gene Simmons clarifies Muslim remarks|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Defamation lawsuit by former girlfriend===\nIn 2005, Simmons was sued by a former girlfriend, Georgeann Walsh Ward, who said she had been \"defamed\" in the [[VH1]] documentary ''When Kiss Ruled the World'' and portrayed as an \"unchaste woman\".<ref>[http://www.law.com/jsp/article.jsp?id=1131640457086 KISS Singer's Motion to Dismiss Defamation Suit Denied]. Law.com. Retrieved February 1, 2011.</ref> A settlement was reached in June 2006.<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,201436,00.html Kiss's Gene Simmons Settles Defamation Suit by Ex-Girlfriend \u2013 Music | Songs | Country | Rap]. FOXNews.com (June 28, 2006). Retrieved February 1, 2011.</ref>\n\n===Views on musical piracy===\nIn 2007, Simmons openly spoke out against [[music piracy]], and called for file-sharers to be sued.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/others/billboard-q-a-gene-simmons-1003671447.story|title=Billboard Q&A: Gene Simmons|work=Billboard|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> A year later, he threatened further lawsuits, and to withhold new recordings, if file-sharing continued. In 2010, [[Anonymous (group)|Anonymous]] staged a [[DDoS]] on his website, prompting Simmons to hit back with provocative comments once he was back online, at which point Anonymous staged a second DDoS, taking Simmons' site down again.<ref name=anonymous>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/news/2010/10/gene-simmons-vs-anonymous-whos-the-bigger-asshole.ars|title=Gene Simmons vs. Anonymous: Who's the bigger tool?|work=Ars Technica|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=2010-10-18}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Simmons said \"The death of rock was not a natural death. Rock did not die of old age. It was murdered\". Simmons blames file sharing and that no one values music \"enough to pay you for it\" for the decline of the rock music scene.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.yahoo.com/news/gene-simmons-rock-finally-dead-murdered-125100515-rolling-stone.html?bcmt=comments-postbox?bcmt=1410126369352-2dea9876-f154-4742-abeb-ebe1edab6b14&bcmt_s=u#mediacommentsugc_container|title=Gene Simmons: 'Rock Is Finally Dead. It Was Murdered'|date=September 7, 2014|work=yahoo.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Comments on suicide and depression===\nIn August 2014, Simmons made comments in an interview with Songfacts.com that seemed to openly encourage people with depression to kill themselves. The comments drew criticism from [[Nikki Sixx]] of [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]] who had suffered from depression in the past.<ref name=\"Sixx\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/gene-simmons-depression-comments-anger-nikki-sixx-20140814|title=Gene Simmons' Depression and Suicide Comments Anger Nikki Sixx|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=2014-08-14}}</ref> Following his comments, both [[Triple M]] and Winnipeg radio station [[Power 97]] stated that they were pulling all Kiss songs from their lineup in protest.<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Neal|first1=Sean|title=Gene Simmons continues asshole tour by telling depressed people to kill themselves|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/gene-simmons-continues-asshole-tour-telling-depres-208204|website=The AV Club|accessdate=August 15, 2014}}</ref> Simmons later clarified his comments and apologized for the incident.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gene Simmons sorry for 'spur of the moment' remarks about mental illness |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/aug/18/gene-simmons-sorry-for-spur-of-the-moment-remarks-mental-illness-depression |website=The Guardian |accessdate=30 May 2018 |language=en |date=18 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Film and television career==\nSimmons has been involved with such television projects as:\n*''[[My Dad the Rock Star]],''<ref name=mcfliker>{{cite news| title = Gene Simmons of KISS: My Dad the Rock Star| first = Todd| last = McFliker| url = http://fatherhoodchannel.com/2013/10/14/gene-simmons-of-kiss-my-dad-the-rock-star-014| publisher=Fatherhood Channel| date = October 14, 2013 |accessdate=October 14, 2013}}</ref> a cartoon by the Canadian animation company [[Nelvana]], about the mild mannered son of a Gene Simmons-like rock star\n*''[[Mr. Romance]]'', a show created and hosted by Simmons on the [[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]] cable television channel\n*''[[Rock School]]'', a UK reality show in which Simmons tries to make a rock band out of a group of students of [[Christ's Hospital School]] in the first season, and in the second, a group of kids from a [[comprehensive school]] in [[Lowestoft]]\n*''[[Gene Simmons Family Jewels]]'',<ref>[http://www.aetv.com/gene-simmons-family-jewels/ Gene Simmons Family Jewels \u2013 A&E TV]. Aetv.com. Retrieved February 1, 2011.</ref> a reality show documenting the personal lives of Simmons, [[Shannon Tweed|his wife]], [[Nick Simmons|his son]] and daughter\n\nIn 1985 Simmons appeared on the TV series ''[[Miami Vice]]'' in and episode titled \"The Prodigal Son\". The episode served as the [[season premiere]] of the show's second season.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Serwer |first=Jesse |date=October 7, 2014 |title=Miami Sound Machine: 16 Best Musical Guest Stars on \u2018Miami Vice\u2019 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/miami-sound-machine-16-best-musical-guest-stars-on-miami-vice-155772/gene-simmons-the-prodigal-son-season-two-27833/ |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York City, United States |publisher=Jann Wenner |access-date=April 27, 2019 }}</ref> Simmons appeared as a psychic working at the Mystic Journey Bookstore in [[Venice, California]] on the American hidden camera prank TV series ''[[I Get That a Lot]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/2010-gene-simmons-poses-as-psychic-for-us-prank-show-news.html|title=Gene Simmons poses as psychic for US prank show|date=January 7, 2010|accessdate=January 14, 2010}}</ref> He also guest-starred as himself in the 2014 ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]'' episode ''Long Road Home''.\n\nSimmons performed in the 1984 [[Michael Crichton]] thriller ''[[Runaway (1984 film)|Runaway]]'' starring [[Tom Selleck]], [[Cynthia Rhodes]] and [[Kirstie Alley]] as well as the 1987 [[Gary Sherman (director)|Gary Sherman]] action film ''[[Wanted: Dead or Alive (1987 film)|Wanted: Dead or Alive]]'' starring [[Rutger Hauer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0094293/|title=Wanted: Dead or Alive (1987)|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015 Simmons founded the film production company Erebus Pictures<ref>{{cite news| title = WWE and Gene Simmons Launch Genre Label; First Film Project Announced \u2013 Temple| first = | last = | url = http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/94783/wwe-and-gene-simmons-launch-genre-label-first-film-project-announced-temple/| publisher=Dread Central| date = March 27, 2015 |accessdate=March 27, 2015}}</ref> and announced as the first project was the Horror-thriller film ''[[Armed Response (2017 film)|Armed Response]]''.<ref>{{cite news| title = If Gene Simmons and WWE\u2019s \u2018Temple\u2019 Is Good, I\u2019ll Eat This Article!| first = | last = | url = http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3337809/gene-simmons-wwes-temple-good-ill-eat-article/| publisher=Bloody Disgusting| date = March 27, 2015 |accessdate=March 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nOn January 28, 2011, Simmons was in [[Dallas]], Texas, to host the Aces & Angels Salute to the Troops charity event. Simmons was presented the key to the city, and a street (Gene Simmons Boulevard) was named for him. Simmons and Tweed also visited the [[U.S. Army]] base at [[Fort Hood]] to support the troops as a part of the Aces & Angels event.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nOn June 15 of the same year he was given the key to the city in [[Winnipeg]], Manitoba. In 2012, Simmons was awarded the ''Golden God'' award by the ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]'' magazine.<ref>[http://www.revolvermag.com/goldengods/revolver-golden-gods-awards-winners-announced/ \u2018Revolver\u2019 Golden Gods Awards Winners Announced!] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202101359/http://www.revolvermag.com/goldengods/revolver-golden-gods-awards-winners-announced/ |date=February 2, 2014 }}. ''revolvermag.com''. April-16-2012; retrieved April 21, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the [[Smithsonian National Museum of American History]] accepted an autographed Gene Simmons Axe bass into their collection. The Smithsonian wrote, in part: \"The bass will now be cared for in our permanent collections... We are happy to include the Axe bass as it relates to the impact Mr. Simmons and his band Kiss have had on American culture, especially in the creation of a unique and iconic brand that has been embraced by fans worldwide ... The story of Mr. Simmons' American experience deserves to be preserved. An immigrant and son of a holocaust survivor, he used creative vision and entrepreneurial acumen to make a significant impact for our nation's popular culture, becoming an iconic figure in American music and entertainment.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kissonline.com|title=KISS Online :: Welcome To The Official KISS Website|first=KISS|last=Online|website=KISS Online|accessdate=July 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSimmons is an honorary board member of Little Kids Rock, a national nonprofit that works to restore and revitalize music education in disadvantaged U.S. public schools. A&E's Gene Simmons Family Jewels visited a Little Kids Rock classroom and featured the segment on the show. He also decorated a guitar for auction with his son Nick.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.littlekidsrock.org/friends/our-big-fans/gene-simmons |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-01-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114071609/http://www.littlekidsrock.org/friends/our-big-fans/gene-simmons/ |archivedate=January 14, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn December 15, 2014, Simmons was awarded the Golden Medal by the Reial Circle Art\u00edstic de Barcelona (Royal Artistic Circle of Barcelona).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/local/barcelona/20141211/54421749733/el-bajista-de-kiss-recibira-el-lunes-la-medalla-de-oro-del-reial-cercle-artistic.html|title=El bajista de Kiss recibir\u00e1 el lunes la medalla de oro del Reial Cercle Art\u00edstic|work=LA VANGUARDIA|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Bandmates\n! Miscellaneous\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Kiss Meets the Phantom of the Park]]''\n| The Demon/Himself\n| [[Peter Criss]], [[Ace Frehley]], [[Paul Stanley]]\n| TV movie\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Runaway (1984 film)|Runaway]]''\n| Dr. Charles Luther\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Never Too Young to Die]]''\n| Carruthers / Velvet Von Ragner\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Trick or Treat (1986 film)|Trick or Treat]]''\n| Nuke (radio DJ)\n|\n| \n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Wanted: Dead or Alive (1987 film)|Wanted: Dead or Alive]]''\n| Malak Al Rahim\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[The Decline of Western Civilization Part II: The Metal Years]]''\n| Himself\n| Paul Stanley\n| Documentary\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''Red Surf''\n| Doc\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Detroit Rock City (film)|Detroit Rock City]]''\n| Himself\n| Peter Criss, Ace Frehley, Paul Stanley\n| Simmons also produced\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Wish You Were Dead]]''\n| Vinny\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[The New Guy]]''\n| Reverend\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Detroit Metal City]]''\n| Jack lll Dark\n|\n| Japanese movie\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Extract (film)|Extract]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/BLABBERMOUTH.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=119334 |title=Gene Simmons To Appear In 'Extract' Film |date=May 3, 2009 |work=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |accessdate=August 14, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606125437/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/BLABBERMOUTH.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=119334 |archivedate=June 6, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n|Joe Adler\n|\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Expecting Mary]]''\n|Taylor\n|\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Rush: Beyond the Lighted Stage]]\n|Himself\n|\n|Documentary\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Incredible Bongo Band|Sample This: The Incredible Story of the Incredible Bongo Band]]\n|Himself\n|\n|Documentary\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Scooby-Doo! and Kiss: Rock and Roll Mystery]]''\n| The Demon\n| Paul Stanley, [[Eric Singer]], [[Tommy Thayer]]\n|Voice only\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[We Are X]]\n|Himself\n|\n|Documentary\n|-\n|2016\n| ''[[Why Him?]]''\n| Himself\n| Paul Stanley\n|Cameo\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Armed Response (2017 film)|Armed Response]]''\n|\n|\n| \n|-\n|TBA\n|''Untitled [[Scooby-Doo! and Kiss: Rock and Roll Mystery]] Sequel''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/KISS/posts/10156223955181412|title=KISS|website=facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n| The Demon\n| Paul Stanley, Eric Singer, Tommy Thayer<ref name=\":0\" />\n|Voice only\n|}\n\n==Television appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Show\n! Episode\n! Role\n! Bandmates\n! Miscellaneous\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[The Mike Douglas Show]]''\n| June 11, 1974\n| Himself\n| Peter Criss, Ace Frehley, Paul Stanley\n| Kiss' first national television appearance, performed \"Firehouse\". \n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[The Paul Lynde Halloween Special]]''\n|October 29, 1976\n|Himself\n| Peter Criss, Ace Frehley, Paul Stanley\n| Performed \"[[Detroit Rock City (song)|Detroit Rock City]],\" \"King of the Night Time World,\" and \"[[Beth (song)|Beth]]\"\n|-\n| 1979\n| Tomorrow\n|\n|Himself\n| Peter Criss, Ace Frehley, Paul Stanley\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Miami Vice]]''\n| \"Prodigal Son\"\n| Newton Blade\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[The Hitchhiker (TV series)|The Hitchhiker]]''\n| \"O.D.Feelin'\"  January 28, 1986\n| Mr. Big\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Action League Now!]]''\n| \"Rock-A-Big-Baby\"\n| Toy version of himself\n| Peter Criss, Ace Frehley, Paul Stanley\n| Performed \"[[Rock and Roll All Nite]]\"\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[MADtv]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planetmadtv.com/forum/showthread.php?t=2129#1|title=Planet MADtv \u2013 ''Episode No.&nbsp;406 (Aired October 31, 1998)''|accessdate=June 5, 2009}}</ref>\n| October 31, 1998 (#406